```

This example creates a customized ToC with page numbers, dots, and flushright formatting. It also includes bibliography entries in the ToC by using the `tocbibind` package. Finally, the ToC is generated using the `\tableofcontents` command. When you compile this LaTeX document, you'll see the customized ToC at the beginning of the document, followed by the chapters, sections, subsections, and bibliography entries.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX and display its state using FEN notation, you can use the `chessboard` package, which provides the necessary commands and styles to create a chessboard and its pieces. Here's an example code that takes a FEN string as input and displays the corresponding chessboard:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\begin{chessboard}[setfen={rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}]
\end{chessboard}
\end{document}
```

This code generates a chessboard with white pieces on the move, with the initial FEN string `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1`. You can adjust the FEN string as needed to display any state of the chessboard.

To display the FEN string along with the chessboard, you can use the `\chessgame` command from the `chessgame` package, which provides a more comprehensive solution for chess notation and analysis in LaTeX. Here's an example code that extends the previous one:

```latex
